segments.text: When you first tried your boots on, did they fit?
At that time, there were two, really just two bootmakers.
There was Hollick and Lucchese out of San Antonio.
I don't know, other than the fact that Hollick would keep them shined all year and we bought them from him, I'm sure they were about the same price.
But Lucchese was really the only other maker.
But that's keeping them shining all year was a pretty good thing.
About how often when you were a student, about your senior year, about how often did you wear your boots?
Mainly just on drill days.
We only drilled once a week or parades.
Now did you go to summer camp?
I sure did.
Where'd you go to?
Fort Crockett, down in Galveston.
Describe that summer camp experience.
Tell me as much as you can remember about it.
Well, there's one part of it I'll never forget.
When I was going to school, I had acne on the back of my neck real bad, and a lot of times I'd have to have those things lanced.
It was just like a rising.
Part of the time I was in A&M I got an excuse not to wear a tie because I couldn't button my collar.
But anyhow, one morning I decided I needed to go to sick call to get my one of those things lanced.
I went over on sick call and the old colonel looked at me and said, put him in the hospital.
The way they got their money was the number of patients they had in the hospital.
Haskell, I was in that thing three damn days.
Never did open that thing.
And I carried meals to the patients.
I shined the doorknobs.
I cleaned the restrooms.
Did everything in the world.
And I thought, why in the world am I in this place?
And the first night they put me in there, it was about full, and they put me in the prison ward.
And in the middle of the night, they brought a prisoner in there who was drunk.
And they put him in there and closed the door.
And we didn't have air conditioning, and the mosquitoes were terrible.
And I lay there with those mosquitoes sailing at me and wondering, now why am I in this darn place?
Now that's one of the things I remember about summer camp.
What did they, what did they, how did they train you all?
Oh, we had rifle practice.
We had, they had some big 12-inch guns there at that time on the seawall.
And the fort, is that one located near the middle of the seawall?
Yeah, there's a big restaurant there now and the embankments are still there where the guns were.
There was two big 12-inch guns and living quarters underneath for all the gun crews and ammunition and all that.
About how many
People were stationed there full time?
Oh, I wouldn't have any idea.
But a hundred or?
Oh, I expect there may have been more than that because there was a complement for those big guns.
But not a thousand?
Oh, I don't imagine.
There was about, as I remember, about two three-story dormitories and that's where they lived.
And how many of y'all were there for the summer?
Well, it was all the senior Coast Artillery people.
Nationwide?
No, no.
Oh.
A&M.
A&M.
I don't think there was any other schools there but us.
I expect there was 150 of us, I imagine.
And you were there for?
Six weeks.
Six weeks.
Six weeks.
What did you and your buddies do for a good time in Galveston?
Well, one thing, we'd walk around in the red light district at night and listen to the gals hollering at you.
On Post Office Street.
Uh-huh.
And, oh, they had some of the best seafood eating places on the seawall.
You could get a shrimp cocktail that big for 25 cents.
You're saying as big as a big salad plate.
That's right.
Were there gambling places in Galveston then?
Later there was.
I don't think it must have been later.
I'm not sure it was at that time.
Of course, I'm sure I know everyone out there.
I don't know whether I know where they were, but it wasn't long after that.
Now did you and your buddies put on your bathing suits and go over and enjoy the beach?
Oh yeah, all the time.
And one Sunday morning, Askel, there was not one wave out there.
And you don't see that very often.
There wasn't an ounce of breeze, and that thing was just as flat as this floor.
You ever see a lot of water like that?
I never seen it before or after.
And hot, it wasn't any fun being out there.
Of course, the fun of the waves, you know.
When you were at summer camp, how well prepared had A&M made you for active duty?
Did you feel fairly well prepared?
Well, I think we did.
We only had one more year, you know.
The things we studied, as I've said before, we studied gunnery, studied small rifles, several of the bigger pieces of artillery, the six-inch guns, 75 millimeters.
They showed us how you take them apart and how you clean them and how they're fired.
We never fired any of the bigger guns, but we did fire the rifles.
Did they talk to y'all that summer about what y'all might be doing if you were called to active duty?
Not really.
One interesting thing about it, when I was called to active duty, that's right where we went back to is Fort Crockett.
They were building an army camp out of Galveston called Fort Crockett, I mean Fort, Camp Wallace.
Camp Wallace, uh-huh.
It was 10, 15 miles up Highway 6 from Galveston, but it wasn't ready.
So our unit, and there was about 3,000,
ultimately in our unit, but they took all the officers and we went down to Fort Crockett and some of the regular army officers called themselves orient and that's for active duty.
That was a couple of months.
Now meanwhile, academically, you're making progress.
As you look back, what were the key courses you took at A&M, the ones that were most important to you in your professional life?
Are you talking about my
My civilian life or Army life?
No, your civilian.
The summer surveying was one of them.
Is that right?
Six weeks of summer surveying.
And you know civil engineers don't take any surveying anymore, I understand.
Another one that was very interesting was what they call structures.
We had a structure there.
I can almost call his name, and he was super.
He had the best notes that you ever did see of, you know, like railroad bridges and trusses.

this sort of thing and that was a real interesting course that to figure if you take one of these big railroad trusses as to what stresses in this beam and what stresses in this and this and all and he could cut one of those things and tell you exactly whether it's tension or compression or you know that was that was interesting.
And you never did think about changing your major?
No.
Got stronger and stronger.
That's right.
And when you were an undergraduate, what were you hoping you were going to get to do?
Go to the highway department.
That's what I really wanted to do.
And when I got out, the highway department had a blanket offer to take all civil engineers that graduated from A&M.
A good many of us did.
Who are some of the teachers that you now realize were most important to you?
Well, this fellow Sandstead, Mac New, Joe Orr.
Joe Orr was, he was the survey man.
That was his baby.
And then we had a number of courses in, I don't know what to call it, but I guess you could call it administration.
you know, as if you were going to be in administrative offices, you know, how to handle people and how to get along with compadres and how to get along with the public and this sort of thing.
I think that was very beneficial.
Did any faculty member ever give you any personal advice that you later realized was very important?
What to do or not to do?
I think they probably were if I could come up with some of them.
I think Joe Orr was one of the ones that sort of aimed us toward the Highway Department.
Joe was a student of the Highway Department because of the surveying.
Mm-hm.
Let's see, talking about linking things together, as you look at your professional life after leaving A&M, what did you learn at A&M that was very important to you in your professional life?
What did you get from A&M that turned out to be significant, important?
Well, one thing is,
getting along with a fellow man.
Aggies were noted for being buddies and getting along with each other.
Of course, a lot of it was forced on them, but I think that was one of the things.
Let me... One specific thing.
This unit that I was called active duty with,
was very unusual.
The enlisted and non-commissioned people were black and the officers were white.
And there were 100 officers called in that unit and 65 of them were A&M graduates.
And we had a better record.
We had better
overall discipline.
A lot of that type of units had worlds of trouble, worlds of trouble.
And we had better discipline.
We had less troubles.
I think our relationship officer to enlisted men was much better because so many of us were used to these people.
We were used to dealing with them.
And we were those
Four years.
Four years.
Now, where did you serve during WWII?
Well, in the States, four years.
After we were activated and got together down at Camp Wallace, we were moved to Camp Davis, North Carolina, right outside of Wilmington.
You got it done?
Uh-huh.
She had a little skin tear on her left arm.
We're talking about A&M and how well you were prepared.
How well did it prepare you to be a highway engineer?
Well, that's really hard to say.
People who wanted to work for the highway department started right on the low end of the totem pole.
I was on the back end of a measuring chain, driving stakes and whatever.
I think, here again, it just prepared me to get educated and take advantage of people who were willing to share with me.
But when you began as a highway engineer,
Was the preparation you had had at A&M up to date?
Oh, yeah, sure.
The main thing I used right off was the surveying that Joe Orr had emphasized.
And then from there on, then I began to get assignments where I had some supervisor responsibilities and a few design responsibilities.
Now, what other schools had high-quality highway programs then?
Was A&M clearly the best?
Well, it got most of the students, as I'm told.
Well, probably Texas got about as many as A&M did, but according to the highway department, A&M
The Texas civil engineers were the ones they preferred, or at least it seemed to be that's where they had the most of them from.
But it's really hard to say.
You know, you look back and you wonder, where did I learn so-and-so?
Or, you know, something comes along.
In fact, I heard one of my instructors one time said,
one of these days you'll make some kind of a decision and you'll think, now where did I learn to do that?
And I guess that's right.
You wonder, where was it that you learned what caused you to make this sort of a thing?
And I guess it's the overall education that does it.
Also, am I correct that had you not gone to A&M, there's no other college you could have afforded to gone to?
That's correct.
I wanted to either.
Of course, I wanted the military part of it.
That was another one of my desires.
I've always enjoyed the military, Haskell.
And N.M. prepared that well, didn't he?
He did.
He did.
And you know,
I even followed it after the war.
I stayed active.
I stayed active in the military.
And you retired what rank?
Brigadier General.
Brigadier General.
And as you saw all of the other ROTC products, how well did A&M's officers compare with the other ROTC officers?
I don't think they could hold light to them.
There sure was a world of people that wanted A&M graduates.
As you look back on A&M, what are the reasons why Aggies have so much pride?
Why are Aggies proud of having gone to school here?
That's a good question.
I guess the easiest way to answer that is just the reputation that A&M has got.
And of course the students are what make the reputation, I guess.
Are there some things that pull people together to help create that reputation?
Well, the Corps is one of the things that pulled a lot of people together.
And of course, in my day, you had to be in the Corps.
So you all felt somewhat of the same feelings and interest in each other.
And are there symbols of that pulling together?
Yeah, sure.
I guess that's the big thing.
Ring?
Yeah.
And boots?
Boots and ring.
Silver tabs?
Yeah.
Football games?
Yeah.
I guess the one thing is the ring.
Like I told you, it's recognized outside of A&M.
When you are no more, what's going to happen to your ring?
To whom does it go?
To A&M, to the former students.
Okay.
Have you ever seen that collection?
Oh, yes.
That's marvelous.
Fantastic.
Nothing like that anywhere else that I know of.
In the world.
Right.
And your senior boots, you still have them.
I have a country place out over in Burleson County, and they're hanging up in the building.
Did you get a saber when you were seen?
Where is it?
I let a friend of mine have it.
Actually it was back at the time, you remember when they couldn't get sabers?
Did you know there was a time when they, and I let him have the saber.
As you were getting ready for your commencement in the spring of 1940,
you went through final review and all that.
Who came to, what loved ones, what family?
Well, my ultimate wife, my mother and father, her mother and father, my brothers and sisters, the whole family was there.
They thought that was pretty special.
I was the first one of any of my family that graduated from A&M.
There's been a bunch of them since.
Right, and were lots of your classmates first generation college students?
Were there lots of your buddies just like you where mom and dad hadn't gone to college?
I really don't know, Haskell.
I wouldn't, I expect there were, but I just don't know, don't know about that.
And do you remember anything about commencement?
Was it held at Guyon Hall?
Mm-hmm.
And was everybody there?
Oh, it was full.
And was your name called?
Did you ever see the old guy in the hall?
Oh, yes.
Was your name called and your hand shaken?
Mm-hmm.
I guess by President Walton, by Walton I'm sure, because I think he was still there at that time.
And then the commandant that issued me my commission.
It was a special day.
As soon as you graduated, did you have orders to report for active duty?
No.
Didn't have that until nine months later.
I had my offer for the Texas Highway Department.
And how much was that offer?
A month?
A month.
What did you think about that salary?
Well, it was the most I'd ever had.
And where was you?
Hearn.
In Hearn?
Hearn.
So you could still live at home?
No, I actually lived in Hearn.
I boarded there until Lucille and I were married, and then we lived in Hearn.
And when did you get married?
August, after I got out in June.
August 10th.
And you rented a place in Hearn.
How much did it cost?
Well, she and I, you mean when we married, $30 a month.
It was a bedroom and a, I guess we shared the bathroom probably.
And a little kitchen.
And what were your duties?
at the highway department, I was put in a field party, staking out center lines and running drainage areas and setting slope stakes and this sort of thing.
And as I said, I was on the other end of the chain, and the old boy that was on the front end of it was about six feet two inches tall and had legs about yea long.
And we'd go across a plowed field, and he could step from one top to the other top, and I'd have to step on top, bottom, top.
He liked to run me to death.
Now, for what highway were you all surveying?
Well, the first job I went out on, they had just done the paving from north of Calvert to Bremond, and we were doing the final estimates on it.
Then the next thing was a little spur up near Buffalo, went off into, away from the highway.
And then it wasn't long after that until we were building one north out of Fairfield.
And then, of course, we ultimately, Highway 6 and 290.
We had several counties that we worked out of.
And so you felt good about that job?
I did.
I was proud of it.
Worked like hell, I tell you.
All right, we're getting ready to kind of summarize this now.
Based on your experience of all sorts, if you were a consultant to A&M today, to the leadership out there, what advice would you give them about the future of A&M?
What would you advise them to do or not to do?
Well, I think a lot of emphasis needs to be put on people being able to work together.
ability to supervise and not drive people, but give them incentives.
You know, the technical things now are all hard.
Like I told you a while ago, they don't teach surveying anymore.
People learn to survey and that's all
farmed out now.
Engineers don't do survey work anymore.
Probably to give a lot of emphasis to, I don't know what I want to say really.
Given good leadership, I guess is what I'm trying to say.
Leadership, I think, is a real important thing.
I've worked in and around a few people that didn't know how to supervise.
And there could be a lot of emphasis in the A&M structure on administrative duties and responsibilities.
Okay.
If you could make a major gift to A&M, somebody hands you a check for a million dollars, but you've got to pass that check on, but you can decide what they do with it.
What would your gift, what would you want it to be for?
It would be hard to say.
What would be your favorite efforts, projects at A&M?
Well, I guess opportunities for disadvantaged students and students who were not able to pay for good education.
And by disadvantage, you're talking about economics.
Yeah, right.
Would it matter what they majored in?
No, I don't think so.
How would you judge their capability?
You mean the individual's capability?
What they could have come.
How do you pick this one instead of that one?
Well, a lot of it I'd have to look back on their high school education and their high school administrators.
I think that would be a key figure.
You know, you got to sort of see how they came up and whether they would take advantage of what you could offer them or not.
And I don't really know how you do that.
to the best advantage, but... Would it matter what the student was going to major in?
No.
Because, you know, the world needs all vocations.
All right.
To what, as you look back, to what people associated with Texas A&M, faculty, students, administrators, do you feel most grateful?
A couple of them are Mr. Hensel and Mr. Horsley for providing me the opportunity to help myself.
And then there was a few of the instructors that had lots to do with it.
And then, not from A&M, but from my parents making it available to me.
A lot of parents don't even,
don't do that.
But those two people really made it possible for me to go to school with A&M.
What have we left out?
I've only got one more question, unless you can think of some things we've left out.
What have we not covered?
Do you remember any goofy moments?
Any sad moments?
I remember one thing, and I didn't know whether I was going to tell you this or not.
I found out that it doesn't pay to let some other student see your work.
And this was in Cuball Rich's class.
An old boy copied off my paper on an examination, and he busted both of us.
But you didn't know he was copying?
No.
And he told us, you know, that two papers are too much alike, and he said if one will admit who did the copying, I'll give the other the grade, and he wouldn't do it.
But that was one of the worst moments I ever got, and I decided right then
You know, I really, I guess I didn't really care if somebody wanted to do it that way, but I found out that it didn't pay.
I wanted to whip his butt, but I had to take it over that summer.
And you didn't have any tragic, any real great sad moments?
No, not really.
What about, were you ever involved in any pranks or jokes or anything like that?
No.
Here, as I said, not leaving on the campus.
I was away from most of that, you know, not being there at night.
All right, then my last question is, what feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M today?
How do you feel about the place now?
Well, of course, I still think it's the greatest place a person can get an education.
And I've been, a lot of my buddies think letting girls go there is the worst thing that ever happened.
And I'm not of that vocation.
I think it's made the university.
It's made the place.
Right now, it'd be a little one-horse school if it wasn't.
But that's one of the big things, in my opinion, and I give credit to Mr. Rutter.
He and I were awful good friends.
Describe examples of that friendship.
Well, we worked together a whole lot, see.
